#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:236
msgid "pytest.mark.xfail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:238
msgid "**Tutorial**: :ref:`xfail`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:240
msgid "Marks a test function as *expected to fail*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:245
msgid ""
"Condition for marking the test function as xfail (``True/False`` or a :ref:"
"`condition string <string conditions>`). If a bool, you also have to specify "
"``reason`` (see :ref:`condition string <string conditions>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:249
msgid "Reason why the test function is marked as xfail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:251
msgid ""
"Exception subclass (or tuple of subclasses) expected to be raised by the "
"test function; other exceptions will fail the test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:253
msgid ""
"If the test function should actually be executed. If ``False``, the function "
"will always xfail and will not be executed (useful if a function is "
"segfaulting)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:256
msgid ""
"* If ``False`` (the default) the function will be shown in the terminal "
"output as ``xfailed`` if it fails   and as ``xpass`` if it passes. In both "
"cases this will not cause the test suite to fail as a whole. This   is "
"particularly useful to mark *flaky* tests (tests that fail at random) to be "
"tackled later. * If ``True``, the function will be shown in the terminal "
"output as ``xfailed`` if it fails, but if it   unexpectedly passes then it "
"will **fail** the test suite. This is particularly useful to mark "
"functions   that are always failing and there should be a clear indication "
"if they unexpectedly start to pass (for example   a new release of a library "
"fixes a known bug)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:257
msgid ""
"If ``False`` (the default) the function will be shown in the terminal output "
"as ``xfailed`` if it fails and as ``xpass`` if it passes. In both cases this "
"will not cause the test suite to fail as a whole. This is particularly "
"useful to mark *flaky* tests (tests that fail at random) to be tackled later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:260
msgid ""
"If ``True``, the function will be shown in the terminal output as "
"``xfailed`` if it fails, but if it unexpectedly passes then it will **fail** "
"the test suite. This is particularly useful to mark functions that are "
"always failing and there should be a clear indication if they unexpectedly "
"start to pass (for example a new release of a library fixes a known bug)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:267
msgid "Custom marks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:269
msgid ""
"Marks are created dynamically using the factory object ``pytest.mark`` and "
"applied as a decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:273
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.timeout(10, \"slow\", method=\"thread\")\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:279
msgid ""
"Will create and attach a :class:`Mark <pytest.Mark>` object to the "
"collected :class:`Item <pytest.Item>`, which can then be accessed by "
"fixtures or hooks with :meth:`Node.iter_markers <_pytest.nodes.Node."
"iter_markers>`. The ``mark`` object will have the following attributes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:283
msgid ""
"mark.args == (10, \"slow\")\n"
"mark.kwargs == {\"method\": \"thread\"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:288
msgid "Example for using multiple custom markers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:290
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.timeout(10, \"slow\", method=\"thread\")\n"
"@pytest.mark.slow\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:297
msgid ""
"When :meth:`Node.iter_markers <_pytest.nodes.Node.iter_markers>` or :meth:"
"`Node.iter_markers_with_node <_pytest.nodes.Node.iter_markers_with_node>` is "
"used with multiple markers, the marker closest to the function will be "
"iterated over first. The above example will result in ``@pytest.mark.slow`` "
"followed by ``@pytest.mark.timeout(...)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:302
msgid "Fixtures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:304
msgid "**Tutorial**: :ref:`fixture`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:306
msgid ""
"Fixtures are requested by test functions or other fixtures by declaring them "
"as argument names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference/reference.rst:309
msgid "Example of a test requiring a fixture:"
